# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mipmapping
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] In 3D computer graphics, **anisotropic filtering** (**AF**) is a technique that improves the appearance of textures, especially on surfaces viewed at sharp angles.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] It helps make textures look sharper and more detailed by reducing blur and aliasing that can occur when surfaces are angled away from the viewer.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] Anisotropic filtering works by applying different amounts of filtering in different directions, unlike simpler methods like bilinear and trilinear filtering which filter equally in all directions.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] While it requires more processing power than these simpler methods, anisotropic filtering became a standard feature in most graphics cards in the late 1990s and is now commonly used in games and other 3D applications, often with user-adjustable settings.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] Anisotropic filtering enhances texture sharpness, counteracting the blur introduced by mipmapping, a common anti-aliasing technique.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] Anisotropic filtering can therefore be said to maintain crisp texture detail at all viewing orientations while providing fast anti-aliased texture filtering.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] In traditional isotropic mipmapping, downsizing at each level halves the resolution on each axis simultaneously.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] As a result, when rendering a horizontal plane at an oblique angle to the camera, the minification would provide an insufficient horizontal resolution due to the reduction of image frequency in the vertical axis.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] That is, when sampling to avoid aliasing on a high-frequency axis, the other texture axes will be similarly downsampled and therefore potentially blurred.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] With mipmap anisotropic filtering, a texture of resolution 256px × 256px would not only be downsampled to 128px × 128px, but also to other non-square resolutions, such as 256px × 128px and 32px × 128px.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] These *anisotropically downsampled* images can be probed when the texture-mapped image frequency is different for each texture axis.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] Then, one axis is not blurred due to the screen frequency of another axis, and aliasing is still avoided.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] Mipmapping and its associated axis-alignment constraints mean it is suboptimal for true anisotropic filtering and is used here for illustrative purposes only.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] More general anisotropic filtering methods support anisotropic probes that are not necessarily axis-aligned in texture space, allowing for diagonal anisotropy.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] Different degrees or ratios of anisotropic filtering can be applied during rendering.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] This degree refers to the maximum ratio of anisotropy supported by the filtering process.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] For example, 4:1 (pronounced “4-to-1”) anisotropic filtering will continue to sharpen more oblique textures beyond the range sharpened by 2:1.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] In practice, this means that in highly oblique texturing situations, a 4:1 filter will be twice as sharp as a 2:1 filter (it will display frequencies double that of the 2:1 filter).
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] However, most of the scene will not require the 4:1 filter; only the more oblique and usually more distant pixels will require the sharper filtering.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] The performance penalty also diminishes because fewer pixels require the data fetches of greater anisotropy.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] Current hardware rendering implementations set an upper bound on this ratio due to the additional hardware complexity and the aforementioned diminishing returns.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] Applications and users are able to adjust the ratio through driver and software settings up to the threshold.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] True anisotropic filtering probes the texture anisotropically on the fly on a per-pixel basis for any orientation of anisotropy.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] In graphics hardware, typically when the texture is sampled anisotropically, several probes (texel samples) of the texture around the center point are taken on a sample pattern mapped according to the projected shape of the texture at that pixel.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] Earlier software methods have used summed-area tables.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] Each anisotropic filtering probe is often in itself a filtered mipmap sample, which adds more sampling to the process.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] Sixteen trilinear anisotropic samples might require 128 samples from the stored texture, as trilinear mipmap filtering needs to take four samples for each of the two mipmaps and then anisotropic sampling (at 16-tap) needs to take sixteen of these trilinear filtered probes.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] However, this level of filtering complexity is not required all the time.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] There are commonly available methods to reduce the amount of work the video rendering hardware must do.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] The anisotropic filtering method most commonly implemented on graphics hardware is the composition of the filtered pixel values from only one line of mipmap samples.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] In general, the method of building a texture filter result from multiple probes filling a projected pixel sampling into texture space is referred to as "footprint assembly", even where implementation details vary.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] The sample count required can make anisotropic filtering extremely bandwidth-intensive.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] Multiple textures are common; each texture sample could be four bytes or more, so each anisotropic pixel could require 512 bytes from texture memory, although texture compression is commonly used to reduce this.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] A video display device can easily contain over two million pixels, and desired application framerates are often upwards of 60 frames per second.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] As a result, the required texture memory bandwidth may grow to large values.
[src:mipmapping/anisotropic-filtering] Ranges of hundreds of gigabytes per second of pipeline bandwidth for texture rendering operations is not unusual where anisotropic filtering operations are involved.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] In computer graphics, a **mipmap** (*mip* being an acronym of the Latin phrase *multum in parvo*, meaning "much in little") is a pre-calculated, optimized sequence of images, each of which has an image resolution which is a factor of two smaller than the previous.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] They are intended to increase rendering speed and reduce aliasing artifacts.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] A high-resolution mipmap image is used for high-density samples, such as for objects close to the camera; lower-resolution images are used as the object appears farther away.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] This is a more efficient way of downscaling a texture than sampling all texels in the original texture that would contribute to a screen pixel; it is faster to take a constant number of samples from the appropriately downfiltered textures.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] Since mipmaps, by definition, are pre-allocated, additional storage space is required to take advantage of them.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] They are also related to wavelet compression.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] Mipmaps are widely used in 3D computer games, flight simulators, other 3D imaging systems for texture filtering, and 2D and 3D GIS software.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] Mipmap textures are used in 3D scenes to decrease the time required to render a scene.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] They also improve image quality by reducing aliasing and Moiré patterns that occur at large viewing distances, at the cost of 33% more memory per texture.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] Mipmapping was invented by Lance Williams in 1983 and is described in his paper *Pyramidal parametrics*.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] From the abstract: "This paper advances a 'pyramidal parametric' prefiltering and sampling geometry which minimizes aliasing effects and assures continuity within and between target images." The referenced pyramid can be imagined as the set of mipmaps stacked in front of each other.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] The first patent issued on Mipmap and texture generation was in 1983 by Johnson Yan, Nicholas Szabo, and Lish-Yann Chen of Link Flight Simulation (Singer).
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] Using their approach, texture could be generated and superimposed on surfaces (curvilinear and planar) of any orientation and could be done in real-time.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] Texture patterns could be modeled suggestive of the real world material they were intended to represent in a continuous way and free of aliasing, ultimately providing level of detail and gradual (imperceptible) detail level transitions.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] Texture generating became repeatable and coherent from frame to frame and remained in correct perspective and appropriate occultation.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] The origin of the term mipmap is an initialism of the Latin phrase *multum in parvo* ("much in little"), and map, modeled on bitmap.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] The term *pyramids* is still commonly used in a GIS context.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] In GIS software, pyramids are primarily used for speeding up rendering times.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] Each bitmap image of the mipmap set is a downsized duplicate of the main texture, but at a certain reduced level of detail.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] Rendering speed increases since the number of texture pixels (*texels*) being processed per display pixel can be much lower for similar results with the simpler mipmap textures.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] If using a limited number of texture samples per display pixel (as is the case with bilinear filtering) then artifacts are reduced since the mipmap images are effectively already anti-aliased.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] Scaling down and up is made more efficient with mipmaps as well.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] If the texture has a basic size of 256 by 256 pixels, then the associated mipmap set may contain a series of 8 images, each one-fourth the total area of the previous one: 128×128 pixels, 64×64, 32×32, 16×16, 8×8, 4×4, 2×2, 1×1 (a single pixel).
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] If, for example, a scene is rendering this texture in a space of 40×40 pixels, then either a scaled-up version of the 32×32 (without trilinear interpolation) or an interpolation of the 64×64 and the 32×32 mipmaps (with trilinear interpolation) would be used.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] The simplest way to generate these textures is by successive averaging; however, more sophisticated algorithms (perhaps based on signal processing and Fourier transforms) can also be used.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] Showing each color channel of each level of an RGB mipmap as a separate plane (left) demonstrates that the whole mipmap forms a square of 4 times the area.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] The increase in storage space required for all of these mipmaps is a third of the original texture, because the sum of the areas 1/4 + 1/16 + 1/64 + 1/256 + ⋯ converges to 1/3.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] This is the inspiration for the tag *multum in parvo*.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] When a texture is viewed at a steep angle, the filtering should not be uniform in each direction (it should be anisotropic rather than isotropic), and a compromise resolution is required.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] If a higher resolution is used, the cache coherence goes down, and the aliasing is increased in one direction, but the image tends to be clearer.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] If a lower resolution is used, the cache coherence is improved, but the image is overly blurry.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] This would be a tradeoff of MIP level of detail (LOD) for aliasing vs blurriness.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] However anisotropic filtering attempts to resolve this trade-off by sampling a non isotropic texture footprint for each pixel rather than merely adjusting the MIP LOD.
[src:mipmapping/mipmap] This non isotropic texture sampling requires either a more sophisticated storage scheme or a summation of more texture fetches at higher frequencies.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] In computer graphics, **texture filtering** or **texture smoothing** is the method used to determine the texture color for a texture mapped pixel, using the colors of nearby texels (ie. pixels of the texture).
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] Filtering describes how a texture is applied at many different shapes, size, angles and scales.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] Depending on the chosen filter algorithm, the result will show varying degrees of blurriness, detail, spatial aliasing, temporal aliasing and blocking.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] Depending on the circumstances, filtering can be performed in software (such as a software rendering package) or in hardware, eg. with either real time or GPU accelerated rendering circuits, or in a mixture of both.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] For most common interactive graphical applications, modern texture filtering is performed by dedicated hardware which optimizes memory access through memory cacheing and pre-fetch, and implements a selection of algorithms available to the user and developer.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] There are two main categories of texture filtering: magnification filtering and minification filtering.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] There are many methods of texture filtering, which make different trade-offs between computational complexity, memory bandwidth and image quality.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] During the texture mapping process for any arbitrary 3D surface, a *texture lookup* takes place to find out where on the texture each pixel center falls.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] For texture-mapped polygonal surfaces composed of triangles typical of most surfaces in 3D games and movies, every pixel (or subordinate pixel sample) of that surface will be associated with some triangle(s) and a set of barycentric coordinates, which are used to provide a position within a texture.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] Such a position may not lie perfectly on the "pixel grid," necessitating some function to account for these cases.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] In other words, since the textured surface may be at an arbitrary distance and orientation relative to the viewer, one pixel does not usually correspond directly to one texel.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] Some form of filtering has to be applied to determine the best color for the pixel.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] Insufficient or incorrect filtering will show up in the image as artifacts (errors in the image), such as 'blockiness', jaggies, or shimmering.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] There can be different types of correspondence between a pixel and the texel/texels it represents on the screen.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] These depend on the position of the textured surface relative to the viewer, and different forms of filtering are needed in each case.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] Given a square texture mapped on to a square surface in the world, at some viewing distance the size of one screen pixel is exactly the same as one texel.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] Closer than that, the texels are larger than screen pixels, and need to be scaled up appropriately — a process known as *texture magnification*.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] Farther away, each texel is smaller than a pixel, and so one pixel covers multiple texels.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] In this case an appropriate color has to be picked based on the covered texels, via *texture minification*.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] Graphics APIs such as OpenGL allow the programmer to set different choices for minification and magnification filters.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] Note that even in the case where the pixels and texels are exactly the same size, one pixel will not necessarily match up exactly to one texel.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] It may be misaligned or rotated, and cover parts of up to four neighboring texels.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] Hence some form of filtering is still required.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] Mipmapping is a standard technique used to save some of the filtering work needed during texture minification.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] It is also highly beneficial for cache coherency - without it the memory access pattern during sampling from distant textures will exhibit extremely poor locality, adversely affecting performance even if no filtering is performed.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] During texture magnification, the number of texels that need to be looked up for any pixel is always four or fewer; during minification, however, as the textured polygon moves farther away potentially the *entire texture* might fall into a single pixel.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] This would necessitate reading **all** of its texels and combining their values to correctly determine the pixel color, a prohibitively expensive operation.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] Mipmapping avoids this by prefiltering the texture and storing it in smaller sizes down to a single pixel.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] As the textured surface moves farther away, the texture being applied switches to the prefiltered smaller size.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] Different sizes of the mipmap are referred to as 'levels', with Level 0 being the largest size (used closest to the viewer), and increasing levels used at increasing distances.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] This section lists the most common texture filtering methods, in increasing order of computational cost and image quality.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] Nearest-neighbor interpolation is the simplest and crudest filtering method — it simply uses the color of the texel closest to the pixel center for the pixel color.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] While simple, this results in a large number of artifacts - texture 'blockiness' during magnification, and aliasing and shimmering during minification.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] This method is fast during magnification but during minification the stride through memory becomes arbitrarily large and it can often be less efficient than MIP-mapping due to the lack of spatially coherent texture access and cache-line reuse.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] This method still uses nearest neighbor interpolation, but adds mipmapping — first the nearest mipmap level is chosen according to distance, then the nearest texel center is sampled to get the pixel color.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] This reduces the aliasing and shimmering significantly during minification but does not eliminate it entirely.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] In doing so it improves texture memory access and cache-line reuse through avoiding arbitrarily large access strides through texture memory during rasterization.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] This does not help with blockiness during magnification as each magnified texel will still appear as a large rectangle.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] Less commonly used, OpenGL and other APIs support nearest-neighbor sampling from individual mipmaps whilst linearly interpolating the two nearest mipmaps relevant to the sample.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] In Bilinear filtering, the four nearest texels to the pixel center are sampled (at the closest mipmap level), and their colors are combined by weighted average according to distance.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] This removes the 'blockiness' seen during magnification, as there is now a smooth gradient of color change from one texel to the next, instead of an abrupt jump as the pixel center crosses the texel boundary.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] Bilinear filtering for magnification filtering is common.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] When used for minification it is often used with mipmapping; though it can be used without, it would suffer the same aliasing and shimmering problems as nearest-neighbor filtering when minified too much.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] For modest minification ratios, however, it can be used as an inexpensive hardware accelerated weighted texture supersample.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] The Nintendo 64 used an unusual version of bilinear filtering where only three pixels are used known as 3-point texture filtering, instead of four due to hardware optimization concerns.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] This introduces a noticeable "triangulation bias" in some textures.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] Trilinear filtering is a remedy to a common artifact seen in mipmapped bilinearly filtered images: an abrupt and very noticeable change in quality at boundaries where the renderer switches from one mipmap level to the next.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] Trilinear filtering solves this by doing a texture lookup and bilinear filtering on the *two* closest mipmap levels (one higher and one lower quality), and then linearly interpolating the results.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] This results in a smooth degradation of texture quality as distance from the viewer increases, rather than a series of sudden drops.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] Of course, closer than Level 0 there is only one mipmap level available, and the algorithm reverts to bilinear filtering.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] Anisotropic filtering is the highest quality filtering available in current consumer 3D graphics cards.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] Simpler, "isotropic" techniques use only square mipmaps which are then interpolated using bi– or trilinear filtering.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] When a surface is at a high angle relative to the camera, the fill area for a texture will not be approximately square.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] Consider the common case of a floor in a game: the fill area is far wider than it is tall.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] In this case, none of the square maps are a good fit.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] The result is blurriness and/or shimmering, depending on how the fit is chosen.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] Anisotropic filtering corrects this by sampling the texture as a non-square shape.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] The goal is to sample a texture to match the pixel footprint as projected into texture space, and such a footprint is not always axis aligned to the texture.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] Further, when dealing with sample theory a pixel is not a little square therefore its footprint would not be a projected square.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] Footprint assembly in texture space samples some approximation of the computed function of a projected pixel in texture space but the details are often approximate, highly proprietary and steeped in opinions about sample theory.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] Conceptually though the goal is to sample a more correct anisotropic sample of appropriate orientation to avoid the conflict between aliasing on one axis vs. blurring on the other when projected size differs.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] In anisotropic implementations, the filtering may incorporate the same filtering algorithms used to filter the square maps of traditional mipmapping during the construction of the intermediate or final result.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] Depth-based shadow mapping can use an interesting Percentage Closer Filter (PCF) with depth-mapped textures that broadens one's perception of the kinds of texture filters that might be applied.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] In PCF a depth map of the scene is rendered from the light source.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] During the subsequent rendering of the scene this depth map is then projected back into the scene from the position of the light and a comparison is performed between the projective depth coordinate and the fetched texture sample depth.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] The projective coordinate will be the scene pixels depth from the light but the fetched depth from the depth map will represent the depth of the scene along that projected direction.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] In this way a determination of visibility to the light and therefore illumination by the light can be made for the rendered pixel.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] So this texturing operation is a Boolean test of whether the pixel is lit, however multiple samples can be tested for a given pixel and the Boolean results summed and averaged.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] In this way in combination with varying parameters like sampled texel location and even jittered depth map projection location a post-depth-comparison average or percentage of samples closer and therefore illuminated can be computed for a pixel.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] Critically, the summation of Boolean results and generation of a percentage value must be performed after the depth comparison of projective depth and sample fetch, so this depth comparison becomes an integral part of the texture filter.
[src:mipmapping/texture-filtering] This percentage can then be used to weight an illumination calculation and provide not just a Boolean illumination or shadow value but a soft shadow penumbra result.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] A *texture map* refers to a 2D image ("texture") that adds visual detail to a 3D model.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] The image can be stored as a raster graphic.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] The coordinate space that converts from a 3D model's 3D space into a 2D space for sampling from the texture map is variously called *UV space*, *UV coordinates*, or *texture space*.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] The UV Coordinates are used to read the color from the texture and apply it to the pixel.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] The original technique was pioneered by Edwin Catmull in 1974 as part of his doctoral thesis.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Texture mapping originally referred to *diffuse mapping*, a method that simply mapped pixels from a texture to a 3D surface ("wrapping" the image around the object).
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] A **texture map** is an image applied ("mapped") to the surface of a shape or polygon.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] This may be a bitmap image or a procedural texture.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] They may be stored in common image file formats, referenced by 3D model formats or material definitions, and assembled into resource bundles.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] They may have one to three dimensions, although two dimensions are most common for visible surfaces.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] For use with modern hardware, texture map data may be stored in swizzled or tiled orderings to improve cache coherency.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Rendering APIs typically manage texture map resources (which may be located in device memory) as buffers or surfaces, and may allow 'render to texture' for additional effects such as post processing or environment mapping.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Texture maps usually contain RGB color data (either stored as direct color, compressed formats, or indexed color), and sometimes an additional channel for alpha blending (RGBA) especially for billboards and decal overlay textures.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] It is possible to use the alpha channel (which may be convenient to store in formats parsed by hardware) for other uses such as specularity.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Multiple texture maps (or channels) may be combined for control over specularity, normals, displacement, or subsurface scattering, e.g. for skin rendering.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Multiple texture images may be combined in texture atlases or array textures to reduce state changes for modern hardware.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] (They may be considered a modern evolution of tile map graphics).
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Modern hardware often supports cube map textures with multiple faces for environment mapping.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Texture maps may be acquired by scanning or digital photography, designed in image manipulation software such as GIMP or Photoshop, or painted onto 3D surfaces directly in a 3D paint tool such as Mudbox or ZBrush.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] This process is akin to applying patterned paper to a plain white box.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Every vertex in a polygon is assigned a texture coordinate (which in the 2D case is also known as UV coordinates).
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] This may be done through explicit assignment of vertex attributes, manually edited in a 3D modelling package through UV unwrapping tools.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] It is also possible to associate a procedural transformation from 3D space to texture space with the material.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] This might be accomplished via planar projection or, alternatively, cylindrical or spherical mapping.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] More complex mappings may consider the distance along a surface to minimize distortion.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] These coordinates are interpolated across the faces of polygons to sample the texture map during rendering.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Textures may be repeated or mirrored to extend a finite rectangular bitmap over a larger area, or they may have a one-to-one unique "injective" mapping from every piece of a surface (which is important for render mapping and light mapping, also known as baking).
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Texture mapping maps the model surface (or screen space during rasterization) into *texture space*; in this space, the texture map is visible in its undistorted form.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] UV unwrapping tools typically provide a view in texture space for manual editing of texture coordinates.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Some rendering techniques such as subsurface scattering may be performed approximately by texture-space operations.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Multitexturing is the use of more than one texture at a time on a polygon.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] For instance, a light map texture may be used to light a surface as an alternative to recalculating that lighting every time the surface is rendered.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] *Microtextures* or *detail textures* are used to add higher frequency details, and *dirt maps* add weathering and variation; this can greatly reduce the apparent periodicity of repeating textures.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Modern graphics may use more than 10 layers, which are combined using shaders, for greater fidelity.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Bump mapping has become popular in video games, as graphics hardware has become powerful enough to accommodate it in real-time.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] The way that samples (e.g. when viewed as pixels on the screen) are calculated from the texels (texture pixels) is governed by texture filtering.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] The cheapest method is to use the nearest-neighbour interpolation, but bilinear interpolation or trilinear interpolation between mipmaps are two commonly used alternatives which reduce aliasing or jaggies.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] In the event of a texture coordinate being outside the texture, it is either clamped or wrapped.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Anisotropic filtering better eliminates directional artefacts when viewing textures from oblique viewing angles.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Texture streaming is a means of using data streams for textures, where each texture is available in two or more different resolutions, as to determine which texture should be loaded into memory and used based on draw distance from the viewer and how much memory is available for textures.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Texture streaming allows a rendering engine to use low resolution textures for objects far away from the viewer's camera, and resolve those into more detailed textures, read from a data source, as the point of view nears the objects.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] As an optimization, it is possible to render detail from a complex, high-resolution model or expensive process (such as global illumination) into a surface texture (possibly on a low-resolution model).
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] This technique is called *baking* (or *render mapping*) and is most commonly used for light maps, but may also be used to generate normal maps and displacement maps.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] The original *Quake* software engine used on-the-fly baking to combine light maps and colour maps in a process called *surface caching*.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Baking can be used as a form of level of detail generation, where a complex scene with many different elements and materials may be approximated by a single element with a single texture, which is then algorithmically reduced for lower rendering cost and fewer drawcalls.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] It is also used to take high-detail models from 3D sculpting software and point cloud scanning and approximate them with meshes more suitable for realtime rendering.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Various techniques have evolved in software and hardware implementations.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Each offers different trade-offs in precision, versatility, and performance.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] In contrast to perpendicular polygons, this leads to noticeable distortion with perspective transformations (as shown in the figure: the checker box texture appears bent), especially as primitives near the camera.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] This distortion can be reduced by subdividing polygons into smaller polygons.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Using quad primitives for rectangular objects can look less incorrect than if those rectangles were split into triangles.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] However, since interpolating four points adds complexity to the rasterization, most early implementations preferred triangles only.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Some hardware, such as the forward texture mapping used by the Nvidia NV1, offered efficient quad primitives.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] With perspective correction, triangles become equivalent to quad primitives and this advantage disappears.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] For rectangular objects that are at right angles to the viewer (like floors and walls), the perspective only needs to be corrected in one direction across the screen rather than both.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] The correct perspective mapping can be calculated at the left and right edges of the floor.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Affine linear interpolation across that horizontal span will look correct because every pixel along that line is the same distance from the viewer.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] In contrast, the original z , u , and v , before the division, are not linear across the surface in screen space.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] It is therefore possible to linearly interpolate these reciprocals across the surface, computing corrected values at each pixel, to produce a perspective correct texture mapping.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] To do this, the reciprocals at each vertex of the geometry (three points for a triangle) are calculated.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Then, linear interpolation can be done on these reciprocals between the n vertices (e.g., using barycentric coordinates), resulting in interpolated values across the surface.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] However, as our division by z altered their coordinate system, this $u_{i},v_{i}$ cannot be used as texture coordinates.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] To correct back to the $u,v$ space, the corrected z is calculated by taking the reciprocal once again: $z_{correct}={\frac {1}{\frac {1}{z_{i}}}}$ .
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] This correction makes it so that the difference from pixel to pixel between texture coordinates is smaller in parts of the polygon that are closer to the viewer (stretching the texture wider) and is larger in parts that are farther away (compressing the texture).
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Affine texture mapping directly interpolates a texture coordinate $u_{\alpha }$ between two endpoints $u_{0}$ and $u_{1}$ : $u_{\alpha }=(1-\alpha )u_{0}+\alpha u_{1}$ where $0\leq \alpha \leq 1$ .
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Various techniques have evolved for rendering texture mapped geometry into images with different quality and precision trade-offs, which can be applied to both software and hardware.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Classic software texture mappers generally only performed simple texture mapping with one lighting effect at most (typically applied through a lookup table), and the perspective correctness was about 16 times more expensive.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] The *Doom* engine restricted the world to vertical walls and horizontal floors and ceilings, with a camera that could only rotate about the vertical axis.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] This meant the walls would be a constant depth coordinate along a vertical line and the floors and ceilings would have a constant depth along a horizontal line.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] After performing one perspective correction calculation for the depth, the rest of the line could use fast affine mapping.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Some later renderers of this era simulated a small amount of camera pitch with shearing which allowed the appearance of greater freedom while using the same rendering technique.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Some engines were able to render texture mapped heightmaps (e.g.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Nova Logic's Voxel Space, and the engine for *Outcast*) via Bresenham-like incremental algorithms, producing the appearance of a texture mapped landscape without the use of traditional geometric primitives.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Every triangle can be further subdivided into groups of about 16 pixels in order to achieve two goals: keeping the arithmetic mill busy at all times and producing faster arithmetic results.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] For perspective texture mapping without hardware support, a triangle is broken down into smaller triangles for rendering and affine mapping is used on them.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] The reason this technique works is that the distortion of affine mapping becomes much less noticeable on smaller polygons.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] The Sony PlayStation made extensive use of this because it only supported affine mapping in hardware and had a relatively high triangle throughput compared to its peers.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Software renderers generally prefer screen subdivision because it has less overhead.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Additionally, they try to do linear interpolation along a line of pixels to simplify the set-up (compared to 2D affine interpolation), thus lessening the overhead further.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Another reason is that affine texture mapping does not fit into the low number of CPU registers of the x86 CPU; the 68000 and RISC processors are much more suited for that approach.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] As the polygons are rendered independently, it may be possible to switch between spans and columns or diagonal directions depending on the orientation of the polygon normal to achieve a more constant z, but the effort seems not to be worth it.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] One other technique is to approximate the perspective with a faster calculation, such as a polynomial.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] A second uses the ${\textstyle {\frac {1}{z_{i}}}}$ value of the last two drawn pixels to linearly extrapolate the next value.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] For the latter, the division is then done starting from those values so that all that has to be divided is a small remainder.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] However, the amount of bookkeeping needed makes this technique too slow on most systems.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] A third technique, used by the Build Engine (used, most notably, in *Duke Nukem 3D*), builds on the constant distance trick used by the *Doom* engine by finding and rendering along the line of constant distance for arbitrary polygons.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Texture mapping hardware was originally developed for simulation (e.g. as implemented in the Evans and Sutherland ESIG and Singer-Link Digital Image Generators DIG) and professional graphics workstations (such as Silicon Graphics) and broadcast digital video effects machines such as the Ampex ADO.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Texture mapping hardware later appeared in arcade cabinets, consumer video game consoles, and PC video cards in the mid-1990s.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] In flight simulations, texture mapping provided important motion and altitude cues necessary for pilot training not available on untextured surfaces.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Additionally, texture mapping was implemented so that real-time processing of prefiltered texture patterns stored in memory could be accessed by the video processor in real-time.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Modern graphics processing units (GPUs) provide specialised fixed function units called *texture samplers*, or *texture mapping units*, to perform texture mapping, usually with trilinear filtering or better multi-tap anisotropic filtering and hardware for decoding specific formats such as DXTn.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] As of 2016, texture mapping hardware is ubiquitous as most SOCs contain a suitable GPU.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Some hardware implementations combine texture mapping with hidden-surface determination in tile-based deferred rendering or scanline rendering; such systems only fetch the visible texels at the expense of using greater workspace for transformed vertices.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Most systems have settled on the z-buffering approach, which can still reduce the texture mapping workload with front-to-back sorting.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Inverse texture mapping instead iterates through pixels on the screen and decides what texel to use for each.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Of these methods, inverse texture mapping has become standard in modern hardware.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] With this method, a pixel on the screen is mapped to a point on the texture.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Each vertex of a rendering primitive is projected to a point on the screen, and each of these points is mapped to a u,v texel coordinate on the texture.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] A rasterizer will interpolate between these points to fill in each pixel covered by the primitive.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] The primary advantage of this method is that each pixel covered by a primitive will be traversed exactly once.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Once a primitive's vertices are transformed, the amount of remaining work scales directly with how many pixels it covers on the screen.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] The main disadvantage is that the memory access pattern in the texture space will not be linear if the texture is at an angle to the screen.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] This disadvantage is often addressed by texture caching techniques, such as the swizzled texture memory arrangement.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] The linear interpolation can be used directly for simple and efficient affine texture mapping, but can also be adapted for perspective correctness.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] Forward texture mapping maps each texel of the texture to a pixel on the screen.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] After transforming a rectangular primitive to a place on the screen, a forward texture mapping renderer iterates through each texel on the texture, splatting each one onto a pixel of the frame buffer.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] This was used by some hardware, such as the 3DO, the Sega Saturn and the NV1.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] The primary advantage is that the texture will be accessed in a simple linear order, allowing very efficient caching of the texture data.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] However, this benefit is also its disadvantage: as a primitive gets smaller on screen, it still has to iterate over every texel in the texture, causing many pixels to be overdrawn redundantly.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] This method is also well suited for rendering quad primitives rather than reducing them to triangles, which provided an advantage when perspective correct texturing was not available in hardware.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] This is because the affine distortion of a quad looks less incorrect than the same quad split into two triangles .
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] The NV1 hardware also allowed a quadratic interpolation mode to provide an even better approximation of perspective correctness.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] UV mapping became an important technique for 3D modelling and assisted in clipping the texture correctly when the primitive went past the edge of the screen, but existing hardware did not provide effective implementations of this.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] These shortcomings could have been addressed with further development, but GPU design has mostly shifted toward using the inverse mapping technique.
[src:mipmapping/texture-mapping] It is possible to use texture mapping hardware to accelerate both the reconstruction of voxel data sets from tomographic scans, and to visualize the results.
